column16: ALEXANDER W DREYFOOS JUNIOR SCHOOL OF THE ARTS
column801: Kaplan is a for-profit organization that has provided test prep for various professional programs and standardized tests for the past 75 years. With its headquarters in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, Kaplan operates across the United States as well as overseas. Its International division conducts services in Europe and the Asia Pacific region. Our project will focus on Kaplan’s Test Prep division, which prepares students for standardized testing using a variety of online and physical classes as well as printed materials. In its mission statement, Kaplan promises five core values:  “integrity, support, knowledge, opportunity, and results.”  Kaplan assures that it “[gives] you the tools you need to succeed” and promises to “open doors and broaden access to education.” In our study, we aim to investigate how—if at all—Kaplan tailors its resources to address the needs of its diverse customer base as it caters to students in the US and abroad.

Our group plans to examine a private New York City preschool through the lens of cultural diversity (economic, racial, religious) by focusing on how the school’s policies and teaching styles either support or detract from a more inclusive school environment that promotes the healthy childhood development of all students. We will look at how these policies impact a school’s community and environment, including both the children and their families. Additionally, we plan on investigating how these institutions promote (or do not promote) cultural diversity. There is ample evidence that early childhood education has long-term educational consequences. The way in which early childhood education incorporates, or ignores, diversity among its students could have enormous consequences on the children’s future.

Our group project will evolve around a diversity program proposed by New York City’s Department of Education called Respect for All. Respect for All is program is an extension of ongoing diversity programs and curriculum-based instruction. During this designated week, the program promotes a respect for diversity as students engage in activities that aim to lessen harassment, intimidation and bullying. The Respect for All program includes several aspects of diversity. We will focus solely on the part including respect for sexual diversity in regard to inclusion of LGBTQ individuals and information regarding the development of gender identity and sexual orientation. We will focus on questions about the program’s goals, implementation and execution of those goals, as well as attitudes towards the program. We will explore the students’ reaction to the program and whether the program have or is expected to cause changes in behavior, both in the general student body and specifically for the students that identify as LGBTQ.

The program of interest for this project is called the Affinity Group Program at the Fieldston School. In this program third, fourth and fifth graders are divided once a week into groups according to their race. This program was created last year and aims to teach children about racial differences and how to navigate racial conflicts in their communities.

Startups nowadays feature a wide variety of micro-cultures stemming from their origins as a group of friends in college or inherited from the subculture from the incubator they originated from. They often have projections of their internal structure through social media and online news articles. We intend to analyze the difference in the perception of these startups’ images from what they portray themselves as in a public forum and what we are able to observe in meeting directly with them.

The goal of this project is to examine and critique how the Interfaith Center of New York (ICNY) approaches the issue of interfaith communication and collaboration from a cultural psychological perspective. We hope to better understand how ICNY attempts to foster dialogue and engagement between different faith congregations. Using this information, we aim to assess the effectiveness of their goals and programming in line with established psychological research.

Our group is most interested in the problem of diversity and inclusion in the work force. When we say diversity, we not only mean racial diversity, but also diversity of gender, religion, etc. Why is diversity in the workplace so important? What makes a work setting more “diverse” than another—can diversity be measured in ways other than simply meeting a quota? And what happens after this quota is reached? A business or company may have reached a certain diversity quota, but what sort of programs are available to increase inclusivity and cohesion? Diversity fosters mutual respect amongst coworkers. It allows for people from all backgrounds, experiences, and mindsets to come together and contribute their share and to give their voice. Having a diverse workplace also aids in conflict resolution, as each employee recognizes and understands each others’ differences. Our proposal is to explore diversity within a media or technology company in an attempt to answer some of these questions.

MTV’s Look Different campaign looks to address racial, gender and anti-LGBT biases by working toward unlearning biases and opening up room for discussions on the different types of biases. The campaign addresses these issues on lookdifferent.org through on-air and digital content. It aims to eradicate subtle forms of discrimination that most individuals unknowingly participate in. Raising concerns such as,  “where do you come from”, “how do you speak such good English” or “you don’t look Jewish”, are examples of subtle discrimination that arise due to our inherent biases. The campaign provides a language for the discussion of such topics that will potentially help youths of different races, gender, and sexuality to feel safer in their school, work or home environment.

Our group is going to study the opportunities granted to women in two different programs within the film industry. The first company we will research is Women Make Movies, a non-profit organization that promotes films produced and directed  by women. We will compare this company’s efforts to that of a larger film production company in New York such as Sony Pictures Classics or the Weinstein Group. We will investigate the opportunities granted to women in both organizations, while also studying the application process for both institutions. This will help us better understand the gender inequality that persists in the film industry based on our prior research. Through this lense, we will attempt to visit both companies to ask questions and observe the company operations. We will ask Women Make Movies how they choose the films they wish to promote. We will also ask if they feel that their work is disregarded in the film industry because of people’s prejudice towards their initiative. How do they go about funding and sponsorship for their company as well? We also will want to look at how well the films they promote do critically, as well as financially. We will compare these answers with what we observe at one of the larger film production companies in NYC. Although we will not be able to ask as direct questions to these companies, we will still want to better understand their application process for employees. We will also ask how they choose the best films to make and who to hire as the best director/actor/etc. We are reaching out to all of these companies at the moment through email and phone to try and set up a site interview and tour. We have decided to work within Columbia Secondary School for Maths, Science & Engineering. Located in Southern Harlem, on 123rd Street, this school opened in June 2007, with the aim of serving "academically talented students who have an interest in a rigorous program focusing on math, science, and engineering" (Columbia Secondary School). More specifically, this school seeks to achieve the challenging goal of selecting underprivileged students and preparing them to enter selective universities, while providing them with a sense of public engagement and ethical responsibility. The only students that have the opportunity to attend Columbia Secondary School are those living in the different neighborhoods of Harlem. The instructional philosophy of Columbia Secondary School is comprised of three main pillars: "setting clear and high expectations, promoting an inclusive and participatory classroom, and motivating students to become independent learners" (Columbia Secondary School).

The Muslim population is the fastest-growing religious community in New York City. There has been a significant increase in recent years of West African Muslims, who choose to settle in Harlem and the South Bronx. The Medina Clinic within Harlem Hospital was established to address the barriers to healthcare that many recent Muslim immigrants face, including

cultural, religious, linguistic, financial, and education issues. The Clinic aims to reach a population that doesn’t typically seek medical treatment, by integrating them into Harlem Hospital Center’s network of services to provide comprehensive primary care, health education, and outreach screening with the cultures and languages of the Islamic community in mind. For example, they claim to tailor their services to religious needs by addressing the need for same- gender providers and adjusting medication regimens for Ramadan.

As a group we have decided to critique Starbucks Coffeehouse. Starbucks is an American coffee company founded in Seattle, and currently has 23,450 locations across the world. In New York City, Starbucks can often be found on every corner, serving items including hot and cold beverages, fruits, pastries, sandwiches, beer, wine, and appetizers. Starbucks stores also sell various types of drinkware such as mugs and thermoses. In addition, the brand’s products such as coffee, ice cream and bottled drinks can be found in many grocery stores.

interested in studying dual language programs in elementary education. Dos Puentes Elementary School (M103), founded in 2012, has a dual language program combining Spanish and English education with the goal of fostering bilingualism within the student body. We specifically would like to investigate the  logistics  of  the  program,  such  as  admissions,  curriculum,  staff  training,  grading,  classroom  dynamics  and language  retention  rates.  In  addition,  our  questions  would  address  the  socio­cultural  factors  that  play  a  role  in language development of students, for example, socioeconomic status, parental involvement, home life, etc. Strategy/Feasibility Plan: We have already reached out to Principal Victoria Hunt, who has agreed to let us examine their dual language program for our project. She put us in contact with Alcira Jaar, the academic coach, who has agreed to meet with us on March 4 (please see attached email). We plan to investigate our questions of interests by visiting Dos Puentes Elementary School and interviewing Alcira Jaar. In our interview, we hope to gain insight on the school’s implementation of the dual language program as well as the academic success of the program thus far. Additionally, we plan to ask Alcira Jaar about the possibility to observe a class in the upcoming weeks to further develop our understanding of the dual language program. If available, we would also like to email teachers to ask about their personal experiences as educators in the program.

Since the majority of our group are seniors, we’ve been actively researching future careers and pathways for post­graduation. One thing that we’ve become increasingly aware of, is the abundance of companies actively focusing on diversity hiring and programs. Companies are becoming aware that there is an increasing need and benefit for diversity receptivity in the workplace, both internally and externally. To illustrate, women and ethnic minorities in particular have become an integral part of a successful workforce. If diversity is handled in the correct manner, the organization is set up for positive human potential (Stevens, Flannery, Victoria, Plaut and Sanchez­Burks 2008). Furthermore, a firm should strive to address diversity in order to improve the productivity of the firm and also to remain competitive in the market. Not only is diversity important in terms of social and economic fairness and morality but it is also crucial in maintaining and increasing profits. Some strategies in working towards diversity include training/education programs, organizational policies to mandate fairness for all employees, mentoring programs for minority employees, and establishing outreach programs, such as internship programs, scholarships, and lectures at schools.

For our project we intend to explore how these issues play out at the New York Times, in the editorial and reporting process they use to select and investigate new stories. We are interested in analyzing how cultural differences in the local environment can impact the reporting process. Our hope is that we will find an opportunity to accompany journalists on site as they try to cover various cultures. We would like to observe how the journalists interact with their subjects and how they may craft their questions to suit those differences. For each visit, we plan to research what is known about the relevant group’s cultural psychology and explore how that might affect how they are presented in the news.

Our project focuses on cultural psychology, representation, and diversity in entertainment, specifically radio and music. The Tiny Desk Concert series showcases a deeply talented and passionate lineup performers, as well as a level of diversity that’s hard to find elsewhere. Our project team is fascinated by this and wants to know more about the process of selecting artists. Ideally, we want to interview someone on the Tiny Desk or All Songs Considered team about inclusion policies, how decisions are made, as well as NPR culture in general.

New Alternative for Children is an organization that facilitates adoption and foster care for children with disabilities. This organization can be observed since they hold daily programs and workshops for children and parents. Not only does this organization work with both new parents who are adopting children, but also with foster care parents as well as the children’s birth parents. This organization works to help create a better environment for these children and a positive culture surrounding disabled children. New Alternatives for Children tries to highlight these children’s abilities and not harp on their disabilities. Programs that we intend to observe are their educational programs along with their workshops that take place with the parents.

The overarching aim of this project is to critique the ways in which L’Oréal targets customers from different cultures. In order to accomplish this, we will explore the processes in which L’Oréal studies and learns about how consumers from different cultures interact with beauty products. We will also identify and explore the aspects of L’Oréal’s corporate culture that are conducive/detrimental to formulating a value proposition that resonates with diverse customers. We believe that our findings could have wide-reaching implications for marketing strategies of other firms competing in the cosmetics industry.

We are looking at studying the local DIY music community, a contemporary punk subculture that centers on a “do-it-yourself” ethic, in Brooklyn.  The DIY community operates on a participant model.  In other words, the audience is not simply a consumerist body.  Instead, the audience contributes to the proliferation of culture directly, making music, art, and zines.  Many times, it will be fellow artists who provide lodging, organize shows, tour with, and attend the concerts of other bands.  It is a community that strives to promote independence, self-expression, and inclusion.  However, the punk culture from which DIY descends has a history of being mostly white and male-dominated.  But the success of the DIY social project is dependent on the comfort of its participants with sharing both artistic and physical spaces, collective interest, and continued support. The community often converges at independently organized shows in spaces such as concert venues or basements to play or listen to music. They are epicenters of cultural exchange, and   we believe that the people running the venues and booking the shows may play a significant role in the culture of community going forward.  We are interested what actions, if any, are taken by venue managers or bookers to encourage or increase diversity.

Our research will focus on diversity in the Junior Division of The Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater.  It  offers  a  diverse  range  of  dance  training  classes  and  performance  opportunities  for children ranging from the age of three to seventeen. Some of these classes include West African dance, Horton dance, jazz, ballet, Spanish dance, and Graham-based modern dance. We want to focus  on  the  diversity  in  the  junior  division  classes,  teachers  in  the  program  and  within  the distribution of scholarship funding.

Sanctuary for Families is a non-profit organization that helps victims of domestic abuse and their families by providing legal assistance, counselling, and other advocacy services. The organization hosts several programs, and our project will specifically focus on the Immigration Intervention Project (IIP), which helps gender violence victims with acquiring citizenship and immigration status. The program works closely with West African and South Asian communities, so attorneys must meet linguistic and cultural needs of clients. Given these demands, our project will analyze how the cultural differences between the attorneys and clients have impacted the interaction between the client and the attorney as well as how the IIP has addressed the training of attorneys to adequately meet these demands.

Our group will conduct research on the Institute of Culinary Education (ICE) located at 225 Liberty St, New York, NY 10281. It was originally established as Peter Kemp’s New York Cooking School in 1975 and renamed to its current name in 2001. ICE offers career training diploma programs in Culinary Arts, Pastry & Baking Arts, Culinary Management, and Hospitality Management. Each year about 1,500 classes are offered in these programs and apart from the main career training programs, ICE offers continuing-education programs (Center for Advanced Pastry Studies, Meet the Culinary Entrepreneurs, Techniques and Art of Professional Bread Baking, and Techniques and Art of Professional Cake Decorating) as well as recreational cooking classes. In 2015, ICE relocated to a new facility in Battery Park City. It provides easy and open access to all of its countless ethnic restaurants, gourmet markets, and culinary resources which helps students learn even more outside of the classroom. ICE calls itself "a hub of multiculturalism". ICC students come from 44 different countries, bringing an international character and dimension to their classrooms.

column801: As a group we have decided to critique Starbucks Coffeehouse. Starbucks is an American coffee company founded in Seattle, and currently has 23,450 locations across the world. In New York City, Starbucks can often be found on every corner, serving items including hot and cold beverages, fruits, pastries, sandwiches, beer, wine, and appetizers. Starbucks stores also sell various types of drinkware such as mugs and thermoses. In addition, the brand’s products such as coffee, ice cream and bottled drinks can be found in many grocery stores.

Our group is most interested in the problem of diversity and inclusion in the work force. When we say diversity, we not only mean racial diversity, but also diversity of gender, religion, etc. Why is diversity in the workplace so important? What makes a work setting more “diverse” than another—can diversity be measured in ways other than simply meeting a quota? And what happens after this quota is reached? A business or company may have reached a certain diversity quota, but what sort of programs are available to increase inclusivity and cohesion? Diversity fosters mutual respect amongst coworkers. It allows for people from all backgrounds, experiences, and mindsets to come together and contribute their share and to give their voice. Having a diverse workplace also aids in conflict resolution, as each employee recognizes and understands each others’ differences. Our proposal is to explore diversity within a media or technology company in an attempt to answer some of these questions.

Sanctuary for Families is a non-profit organization that helps victims of domestic abuse and their families by providing legal assistance, counselling, and other advocacy services. The organization hosts several programs, and our project will specifically focus on the Immigration Intervention Project (IIP), which helps gender violence victims with acquiring citizenship and immigration status. The program works closely with West African and South Asian communities, so attorneys must meet linguistic and cultural needs of clients. Given these demands, our project will analyze how the cultural differences between the attorneys and clients have impacted the interaction between the client and the attorney as well as how the IIP has addressed the training of attorneys to adequately meet these demands.

American Ballet Theatre is recognized as one of the greatest and the most representative American ballet companies due to its size, quality, and organizational scope. In September 2013, the company introduced Project Plié, a comprehensive initiative to increase racial and ethnic representation in ballet and diversify America’s ballet companies. The mission of this project is to offer support and training to students from underrepresented racial, ethnic and socio-economic groups in order to increase opportunities for young students and nurture talent among all backgrounds. The hope is that this initiative will connect training-level students with active, professional engagement from teachers, mentors and professional dancers.

Kaplan is a for-profit organization that has provided test prep for various professional programs and standardized tests for the past 75 years. With its headquarters in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, Kaplan operates across the United States as well as overseas. Its International division conducts services in Europe and the Asia Pacific region. Our project will focus on Kaplan’s Test Prep division, which prepares students for standardized testing using a variety of online and physical classes as well as printed materials. In its mission statement, Kaplan promises five core values:  “integrity, support, knowledge, opportunity, and results.”  Kaplan assures that it “[gives] you the tools you need to succeed” and promises to “open doors and broaden access to education.” In our study, we aim to investigate how—if at all—Kaplan tailors its resources to address the needs of its diverse customer base as it caters to students in the US and abroad.

New Alternative for Children is an organization that facilitates adoption and foster care for children with disabilities. This organization can be observed since they hold daily programs and workshops for children and parents. Not only does this organization work with both new parents who are adopting children, but also with foster care parents as well as the children’s birth parents. This organization works to help create a better environment for these children and a positive culture surrounding disabled children. New Alternatives for Children tries to highlight these children’s abilities and not harp on their disabilities. Programs that we intend to observe are their educational programs along with their workshops that take place with the parents.

For our project we intend to explore how these issues play out at the New York Times, in the editorial and reporting process they use to select and investigate new stories. We are interested in analyzing how cultural differences in the local environment can impact the reporting process. Our hope is that we will find an opportunity to accompany journalists on site as they try to cover various cultures. We would like to observe how the journalists interact with their subjects and how they may craft their questions to suit those differences. For each visit, we plan to research what is known about the relevant group’s cultural psychology and explore how that might affect how they are presented in the news.

We are looking at studying the local DIY music community, a contemporary punk subculture that centers on a “do-it-yourself” ethic, in Brooklyn.  The DIY community operates on a participant model.  In other words, the audience is not simply a consumerist body.  Instead, the audience contributes to the proliferation of culture directly, making music, art, and zines.  Many times, it will be fellow artists who provide lodging, organize shows, tour with, and attend the concerts of other bands.  It is a community that strives to promote independence, self-expression, and inclusion.  However, the punk culture from which DIY descends has a history of being mostly white and male-dominated.  But the success of the DIY social project is dependent on the comfort of its participants with sharing both artistic and physical spaces, collective interest, and continued support. The community often converges at independently organized shows in spaces such as concert venues or basements to play or listen to music. They are epicenters of cultural exchange, and   we believe that the people running the venues and booking the shows may play a significant role in the culture of community going forward.  We are interested what actions, if any, are taken by venue managers or bookers to encourage or increase diversity.

Our group project will evolve around a diversity program proposed by New York City’s Department of Education called Respect for All. Respect for All is program is an extension of ongoing diversity programs and curriculum-based instruction. During this designated week, the program promotes a respect for diversity as students engage in activities that aim to lessen harassment, intimidation and bullying. The Respect for All program includes several aspects of diversity. We will focus solely on the part including respect for sexual diversity in regard to inclusion of LGBTQ individuals and information regarding the development of gender identity and sexual orientation. We will focus on questions about the program’s goals, implementation and execution of those goals, as well as attitudes towards the program. We will explore the students’ reaction to the program and whether the program have or is expected to cause changes in behavior, both in the general student body and specifically for the students that identify as LGBTQ.

We would like to investigate the diversity initiative at New York’s Fire Department. The controversy surrounding the largely white and male FDNY has led to efforts to increase diversity in  its  recruiting  process.  These  policies  include  diversity  recruitment  and  training  programs,  a racial quota, and the appointment of a Diversity and Inclusion Officer.

MTV’s Look Different campaign looks to address racial, gender and anti-LGBT biases by working toward unlearning biases and opening up room for discussions on the different types of biases. The campaign addresses these issues on lookdifferent.org through on-air and digital content. It aims to eradicate subtle forms of discrimination that most individuals unknowingly participate in. Raising concerns such as,  “where do you come from”, “how do you speak such good English” or “you don’t look Jewish”, are examples of subtle discrimination that arise due to our inherent biases. The campaign provides a language for the discussion of such topics that will potentially help youths of different races, gender, and sexuality to feel safer in their school, work or home environment.

Our group will conduct research on the Institute of Culinary Education (ICE) located at 225 Liberty St, New York, NY 10281. It was originally established as Peter Kemp’s New York Cooking School in 1975 and renamed to its current name in 2001. ICE offers career training diploma programs in Culinary Arts, Pastry & Baking Arts, Culinary Management, and Hospitality Management. Each year about 1,500 classes are offered in these programs and apart from the main career training programs, ICE offers continuing-education programs (Center for Advanced Pastry Studies, Meet the Culinary Entrepreneurs, Techniques and Art of Professional Bread Baking, and Techniques and Art of Professional Cake Decorating) as well as recreational cooking classes. In 2015, ICE relocated to a new facility in Battery Park City. It provides easy and open access to all of its countless ethnic restaurants, gourmet markets, and culinary resources which helps students learn even more outside of the classroom. ICE calls itself "a hub of multiculturalism". ICC students come from 44 different countries, bringing an international character and dimension to their classrooms.

Therefore, it is important to understand how this organization handles issues of cultural diversity.

We plan on conducting an analysis of diversity and attempts to improve diversity in the workplace at the Facebook/Instagram, Pinterest, and Twitter New York offices. Sites such as Twitter and Pinterest have hired chiefs of diversity in order to help with diversity efforts, and we will see if these effort have proven effective or not. Pinterest has also implemented the Rooney Rule Requirement in an effort to hire more minority employees.

Since the majority of our group are seniors, we’ve been actively researching future careers and pathways for post­graduation. One thing that we’ve become increasingly aware of, is the abundance of companies actively focusing on diversity hiring and programs. Companies are becoming aware that there is an increasing need and benefit for diversity receptivity in the workplace, both internally and externally. To illustrate, women and ethnic minorities in particular have become an integral part of a successful workforce. If diversity is handled in the correct manner, the organization is set up for positive human potential (Stevens, Flannery, Victoria, Plaut and Sanchez­Burks 2008). Furthermore, a firm should strive to address diversity in order to improve the productivity of the firm and also to remain competitive in the market. Not only is diversity important in terms of social and economic fairness and morality but it is also crucial in maintaining and increasing profits. Some strategies in working towards diversity include training/education programs, organizational policies to mandate fairness for all employees, mentoring programs for minority employees, and establishing outreach programs, such as internship programs, scholarships, and lectures at schools.

We have decided to work within Columbia Secondary School for Maths, Science & Engineering. Located in Southern Harlem, on 123rd Street, this school opened in June 2007, with the aim of serving "academically talented students who have an interest in a rigorous program focusing on math, science, and engineering" (Columbia Secondary School). More specifically, this school seeks to achieve the challenging goal of selecting underprivileged students and preparing them to enter selective universities, while providing them with a sense of public engagement and ethical responsibility. The only students that have the opportunity to attend Columbia Secondary School are those living in the different neighborhoods of Harlem. The instructional philosophy of Columbia Secondary School is comprised of three main pillars: "setting clear and high expectations, promoting an inclusive and participatory classroom, and motivating students to become independent learners" (Columbia Secondary School).

Our group plans to examine a private New York City preschool through the lens of cultural diversity (economic, racial, religious) by focusing on how the school’s policies and teaching styles either support or detract from a more inclusive school environment that promotes the healthy childhood development of all students. We will look at how these policies impact a school’s community and environment, including both the children and their families. Additionally, we plan on investigating how these institutions promote (or do not promote) cultural diversity. There is ample evidence that early childhood education has long-term educational consequences. The way in which early childhood education incorporates, or ignores, diversity among its students could have enormous consequences on the children’s future.

column801: Our group is going to study the opportunities granted to women in two different programs within the film industry. We will investigate the opportunities granted to women in both organizations, while also studying the application process for both institutions. This will help us better understand the gender inequality that persists in the film industry based on our prior research. Through this lense, we will attempt to visit both companies to ask questions and observe the company operations. We will ask Women Make Movies how they choose the films they wish to promote. We will also ask if they feel that their work is disregarded in the film industry because of people’s prejudice towards their initiative. How do they go about funding and sponsorship for their company as well? We also will want to look at how well the films they promote do critically, as well as financially. We will compare these answers with what we observe at one of the larger film production companies in NYC. Although we will not be able to ask as direct questions to these companies, we will still want to better understand their application process for employees. We are looking at studying the local DIY music community, a contemporary punk subculture that centers on a “do-it-yourself” ethic, in Brooklyn.  The DIY community operates on a participant model.  In other words, the audience is not simply a consumerist body.  Instead, the audience contributes to the proliferation of culture directly, making music, art, and zines.  Many times, it will be fellow artists who provide lodging, organize shows, tour with, and attend the concerts of other bands.  It is a community that strives to promote independence, self-expression, and inclusion.  However, the punk culture from which DIY descends has a history of being mostly white and male-dominated.  But the success of the DIY social project is dependent on the comfort of its participants with sharing both artistic and physical spaces, collective interest, and continued support. The community often converges at independently organized shows in spaces such as concert venues or basements to play or listen to music. They are epicenters of cultural exchange, and   we believe that the people running the venues and booking the shows may play a significant role in the culture of community going forward.  We are interested what actions, if any, are taken by venue managers or bookers to encourage or increase diversity.

We plan to study the diversity programs that Facebook employs. Facebook is an integral part of everyday life for more than a billion people around the world (Facebook, 2016), used for everything from connecting with friends to providing a platform for social and political dialogues. Therefore, it is important to understand how this organization handles issues of cultural diversity.

column801: We plan on conducting an analysis of diversity and attempts to improve diversity in the workplace at the Facebook/Instagram, Pinterest, and Twitter New York offices. Sites such as Twitter and Pinterest have hired chiefs of diversity in order to help with diversity efforts, and we will see if these effort have proven effective or not. MTV’s Look Different campaign looks to address racial, gender and anti-LGBT biases by working toward unlearning biases and opening up room for discussions on the different types of biases. The campaign addresses these issues on lookdifferent.org through on-air and digital content. It aims to eradicate subtle forms of discrimination that most individuals unknowingly participate in. Raising concerns such as,  “where do you come from”, “how do you speak such good English” or “you don’t look Jewish”, are examples of subtle discrimination that arise due to our inherent biases. The campaign provides a language for the discussion of such topics that will potentially help youths of different races, gender, and sexuality to feel safer in their school, work or home environment.

The overarching aim of this project is to critique the ways in which L’Oréal targets customers from different cultures. In order to accomplish this, we will explore the processes in which L’Oréal studies and learns about how consumers from different cultures interact with beauty products. We will also identify and explore the aspects of L’Oréal’s corporate culture that are conducive/detrimental to formulating a value proposition that resonates with diverse customers. We believe that our findings could have wide-reaching implications for marketing strategies of other firms competing in the cosmetics industry.

For our project we intend to explore how these issues play out at the New York Times, in the editorial and reporting process they use to select and investigate new stories. We are interested in analyzing how cultural differences in the local environment can impact the reporting process. Our hope is that we will find an opportunity to accompany journalists on site as they try to cover various cultures. We would like to observe how the journalists interact with their subjects and how they may craft their questions to suit those differences. For each visit, we plan to research what is known about the relevant group’s cultural psychology and explore how that might affect how they are presented in the news.

Our research will focus on diversity in the Junior Division of The Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater.  It  offers  a  diverse  range  of  dance  training  classes  and  performance  opportunities  for children ranging from the age of three to seventeen. Some of these classes include West African dance, Horton dance, jazz, ballet, Spanish dance, and Graham-based modern dance. We want to focus  on  the  diversity  in  the  junior  division  classes,  teachers  in  the  program  and  within  the distribution of scholarship funding.

We hope to better understand how ICNY attempts to foster dialogue and engagement between different faith congregations. Using this information, we aim to assess the effectiveness of their goals and programming in line with established psychological research.

Our group is going to study the opportunities granted to women in two different programs within the film industry. The first company we will research is Women Make Movies, a non-profit organization that promotes films produced and directed  by women. We will compare this company’s efforts to that of a larger film production company in New York such as Sony Pictures Classics or the Weinstein Group. We will investigate the opportunities granted to women in both organizations, while also studying the application process for both institutions. This will help us better understand the gender inequality that persists in the film industry based on our prior research. Through this lense, we will attempt to visit both companies to ask questions and observe the company operations. We will ask Women Make Movies how they choose the films they wish to promote. We will also ask if they feel that their work is disregarded in the film industry because of people’s prejudice towards their initiative. How do they go about funding and sponsorship for their company as well? We also will want to look at how well the films they promote do critically, as well as financially. We will compare these answers with what we observe at one of the larger film production companies in NYC. Although we will not be able to ask as direct questions to these companies, we will still want to better understand their application process for employees. We will also ask how they choose the best films to make and who to hire as the best director/actor/etc. We are reaching out to all of these companies at the moment through email and phone to try and set up a site interview and tour. Additionally, we plan to ask Alcira Jaar about the possibility to observe a class in the upcoming weeks to further develop our understanding of the dual language program. If available, we would also like to email teachers to ask about their personal experiences as educators in the program.

American Ballet Theatre is recognized as one of the greatest and the most representative American ballet companies due to its size, quality, and organizational scope. In September 2013, the company introduced Project Plié, a comprehensive initiative to increase racial and ethnic representation in ballet and diversify America’s ballet companies. The mission of this project is to offer support and training to students from underrepresented racial, ethnic and socio-economic groups in order to increase opportunities for young students and nurture talent among all backgrounds. The hope is that this initiative will connect training-level students with active, professional engagement from teachers, mentors and professional dancers.

column16: ST JOSEPH HILL ACADEMY HIGH SCHOOL
column801: Our group will conduct research on the Institute of Culinary Education (ICE) located at 225 Liberty St, New York, NY 10281. It was originally established as Peter Kemp’s New York Cooking School in 1975 and renamed to its current name in 2001. ICE offers career training diploma programs in Culinary Arts, Pastry & Baking Arts, Culinary Management, and Hospitality Management. Each year about 1,500 classes are offered in these programs and apart from the main career training programs, ICE offers continuing-education programs (Center for Advanced Pastry Studies, Meet the Culinary Entrepreneurs, Techniques and Art of Professional Bread Baking, and Techniques and Art of Professional Cake Decorating) as well as recreational cooking classes. In 2015, ICE relocated to a new facility in Battery Park City. It provides easy and open access to all of its countless ethnic restaurants, gourmet markets, and culinary resources which helps students learn even more outside of the classroom. ICE calls itself "a hub of multiculturalism". ICC students come from 44 different countries, bringing an international character and dimension to their classrooms.

The program of interest for this project is called the Affinity Group Program at the Fieldston School. In this program third, fourth and fifth graders are divided once a week into groups according to their race. This program was created last year and aims to teach children about racial differences and how to navigate racial conflicts in their communities.

Our group project will evolve around a diversity program proposed by New York City’s Department of Education called Respect for All. Respect for All is program is an extension of ongoing diversity programs and curriculum-based instruction. During this designated week, the program promotes a respect for diversity as students engage in activities that aim to lessen harassment, intimidation and bullying. The Respect for All program includes several aspects of diversity. We will focus solely on the part including respect for sexual diversity in regard to inclusion of LGBTQ individuals and information regarding the development of gender identity and sexual orientation. We will focus on questions about the program’s goals, implementation and execution of those goals, as well as attitudes towards the program. We will explore the students’ reaction to the program and whether the program have or is expected to cause changes in behavior, both in the general student body and specifically for the students that identify as LGBTQ.

New Alternative for Children is an organization that facilitates adoption and foster care for children with disabilities. This organization can be observed since they hold daily programs and workshops for children and parents. Not only does this organization work with both new parents who are adopting children, but also with foster care parents as well as the children’s birth parents. This organization works to help create a better environment for these children and a positive culture surrounding disabled children. New Alternatives for Children tries to highlight these children’s abilities and not harp on their disabilities. Programs that we intend to observe are their educational programs along with their workshops that take place with the parents.
